For Project 2, I will be using The Movies Dataset from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/rounakbanik/the-movies-dataset/home

The dataset contains information from TMDB and GroupLens. I will be focusing on movie ratings.

So since there are a LOT of duplicates (9066/10004 = 0.09), we will have to deal with the data accordingly. Each movie is voted on an average of 10 times, and with 671 users that means that there is a lot of different movies and some may have a lot of ratings and a lot may have only one.

Modifying Data

Averaging rating

Im not quite sure how the popularity column in the reference table has been calculated, but I want to work with average ratings for movies, not individual ratings. So I will use summarize to create a new kind of rating table.

avged <- ratings %>%
  group_by(movieId) %>%
  summarize(avg_rating = mean(rating), rating_count = n()) %>%
  print
## # A tibble: 9,066  3
##    movieId avg_rating rating_count
##      <int>      <dbl>        <int>
## 1        1   3.872470          247
## 2        2   3.401869          107
## 3        3   3.161017           59
## 4        4   2.384615           13
## 5        5   3.267857           56
## 6        6   3.884615          104
## 7        7   3.283019           53
## 8        8   3.800000            5
## 9        9   3.150000           20
## 10      10   3.450820          122
## # ... with 9,056 more rows

Perfect. Now we can do a preliminary graph, even though we dont know very much about what kinds of movies there are or even which movies are which.

x <- ggplot(avged, aes(x = avg_rating)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, color = "blue", fill = "pink")
x

This is divided into bins of 0.5 rating, since we kind of made the ratings into a continuous variable by averaging it.

Merging Movie Metadata and Average Ratings

I want to be able to compare movies based on other attributes, though, so lets put the two dataframes together. Looks pretty cool with all the movieIds lined up.

Just to make sure that were really only looking at movies that enough people are watching and ratings are not skewed because of too few ratings, lets filter out all movies with 7 or less rating_count. (This is actually very effective and important! We go down from 9076 rows to 2592.)

final <- merge(avged, ref, by.x = "movieId", by.y = "id", all.x = TRUE)

Random 100 Movies Intermission Break

We take an intermission here to let you randomly select 100 movies to see where they rank, so you can read their titles. I organized their ranking in color so its easier to parse, and also look at that fancy ggrepel. Sweet. Each time you run this chunk, the 100 movies will be different. Its probably going to be sorrily permanent in knit, though.

new <- final
len <- nrow(final)
new$random <- runif(len)
new$divs <- cut(new$avg_rating, breaks = c(0, 2.5, 3.0, 3.5, 4.0, 4.5, 5))
n <- ggplot(new[sample.int(len, 100),], aes(x = avg_rating, y = random, label = title, color = divs)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_label_repel(size = 5)
n
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_label_repel).

Searching For A Trend, Some Correlation

Lets compare popularity and average rating and see if that had anything to do with each other.

y <- ggplot(final, aes(x = avg_rating, y = popularity)) +
  geom_jitter()
y
## Warning: Removed 350 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Okay, so it doesnt look like theres much of a correlation between popularity and rating. Also, for some reason, there are a few (350) rows with NAs, so those were omitted from the graph.

Im not quite sure what vote_average means, so lets check that out against avg_rating.

z <- ggplot(final, aes(x = avg_rating, y = vote_average)) +
  geom_jitter()
z
## Warning: Removed 350 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Okay, this looks a little more promising. There seems to be a clump towards the middle, with about 3.5 rating and an average of around 6.25. There are apparently a lot of movies with a vote_average of 0, presumably because someone didnt enter any data for that movie, which makes a line on the bottom. They probably should have said NA instead.

Still, there is no clear trend, just a centralization of the data. Lets keep going and see if we can find any interesting trends. Lets try revenue.

a <- ggplot(final, aes(x = avg_rating, y = revenue)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_text(aes(label=ifelse(revenue > 450000000, as.character(title), '')),hjust = 0,vjust = 0)
a
## Warning: Removed 350 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 350 rows containing missing values (geom_text).

So maybe not. But surely popularity was somehow calculated based on revenue?

b <- ggplot(final, aes(x = popularity, y = revenue)) +
  geom_jitter()
b
## Warning: Removed 350 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

You know, if not, then okay, man. Another problem was that a lot of the revenue columns are set to 0 (which I think probably should have been NAs). I wonder if we can find any interesting correlations at all.

Filtering By Recent Movies

How about release date? What about just knowing about movies from the 2010s?

recent <- filter(final, release_date > "2010-01-01")
recent$random <- runif(419)

c <- ggplot(recent, aes(x = avg_rating, y = random)) +
  geom_point()
c

Still not very meaningful, but at least weve got less dots. Not sure what attributes we have access to that would help us figure out what makes the best rated movies the best. I guess we can still find out which ones are the best.
